## Setup

```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

Dependencies: `requests`, `feedparser` (see `requirements.txt`).

### Environment variables

| Variable | Purpose |
|----------|---------|
| `ARXIV_CONTACT_EMAIL` | Included in `User-Agent` (recommended by arXiv). |
| `ARXIV_REQUEST_DELAY` | Seconds between HTTP calls for arXiv (default `3.0`). |
| `CROSSREF_REQUEST_DELAY` | Seconds between HTTP calls for Crossref (default `0.5`). |
| `SEMANTIC_SCHOLAR_REQUEST_DELAY` | Seconds between HTTP calls for Semantic Scholar (default `1.0`). |
| `REFSPROJ_LOG_LEVEL` | Default log level if you omit `--log-level`. |
| `REFSPROJ_LOG_CONFIG` | Path to a custom logging `fileConfig` INI (overrides built-in file setup when used). |

---

## Project layout

| Path | Role |
|------|------|
| `app.py` | CLI entry. |
| `app.bat` | Windows launcher (`cd` to script dir, `python app.py %*`). |
| `src/` | `search`, `bibtex`, `md_smart`, `ref_logging`, `config`. |
| `refs/` | Default output for relative `.bib` / `.md` paths. |
| `logs/app.log` | Rotating log (with built-in logging config). |
| `logging.conf` | Optional INI; if it contains `[sections]`, it is loaded from project root. |

Relative **output** paths (`-o`) are resolved under **`refs/`** unless you pass an **absolute** path. **`..`** is rejected in relative paths.

---

## Global options & logging

Place **before** the subcommand: `bulk`, `match`, or `smart`.

| Flag | Meaning |
|------|---------|
| `-v`, `--verbose` | Console logging at **DEBUG**. |
| `--log-level` | e.g. `INFO`, `WARNING`, `DEBUG`. |
| `--no-log-file` | Stderr only when using the **built-in** dict config (see note below). |

**Built-in logging:** stderr + rotating **`logs/app.log`** (about 1 MB × 5 backups).

**Note:** If `logging.conf` in the project root defines real INI sections, `fileConfig` runs first; `--no-log-file` may not remove handlers defined only in that file.

```bash
python app.py -v bulk -q 'all:transformer' -n 3
python app.py --log-level DEBUG match -t "attention is all you need" -y
python app.py --no-log-file bulk -q 'cat:cs.CL' -n 5
python app.py -v smart notes.md -o cited.md
```

---

## Command: `bulk`

```bash
python app.py bulk --help
```

| Flag | Default | Description |
|------|---------|-------------|
| `-q`, `--query` | *(required)* | Search query. For arXiv, use `all:keywords`, `ti:title`, etc. For others, plain keywords. |
| `-n`, `--max-results` | `50` | Max papers (fetched in pages up to 100). |
| `-o`, `--output` | `arxiv_references.bib` | Output path; split mode uses its **parent** as the folder for per-paper files. |
| `--split` | off | One `.bib` per paper; **filename from sanitized title** (duplicates → id suffix). |
| `--session` | off | With `--split`, write under **`YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS/`** inside that parent. |
| `--sort-by` | `submittedDate` | e.g. `relevance`, `lastUpdatedDate`. |
| `--sort-order` | `descending` | `ascending` or `descending`. |
| `--api` | `arxiv` | `arxiv`, `crossref`, `semantic_scholar`, or `all` (merges & deduplicates). |

**Split output directory**

- `-o out.bib --split` → files in **`refs/`** (parent of `refs/out.bib`).
- `-o batch/run.bib --split` → **`refs/batch/`**.
- `--split --session` → **`refs/<timestamp>/`** (or `refs/batch/<timestamp>/` when parent is `refs/batch`).

```bash
python app.py bulk -q 'cat:cs.CL AND all:survey' -n 20
python app.py bulk -q 'all:"large language model"' -n 15 -o llm_survey.bib
python app.py bulk -q 'ti:diffusion' -n 10 --sort-by relevance --sort-order ascending
python app.py bulk -q 'cat:cs.LG' -n 10 -o run.bib --split
python app.py bulk -q 'cat:cs.CL' -n 10 -o run.bib --split --session
python app.py bulk -q 'all:water' -n 5 -o mybatch/export.bib --split
python app.py -v bulk -q 'all:electron' -n 3 -o test.bib

# Multi-API examples
python app.py bulk -q "machine learning" --api crossref -n 20
python app.py bulk -q "transformer" --api semantic_scholar -n 10
python app.py bulk -q "neural network" --api all -n 30  # Merged results
```

**Query syntax by API:**
- **arXiv**: `all:keywords`, `ti:words`, `au:name`, `cat:cs.CL`, combined with `AND`. See [arXiv API manual](https://info.arxiv.org/help/api/user-manual.html).
- **Crossref/Semantic Scholar**: Plain keyword phrases work best.
- **PowerShell**: Use single quotes where possible; quoting differs from bash.

---

## Command: `match`

```bash
python app.py match --help
```

| Flag | Default | Description |
|------|---------|-------------|
| `-t`, `--title` | *(empty)* | Title substring; required unless `-i`. |
| `-n`, `--max-results` | `100` | Candidate pool before fuzzy ranking. |
| `-o`, `--output` | `paper_citation.bib` | Output `.bib` under `refs/` if relative. |
| `--pick` | `1` | 1-based rank after sort. |
| `--min-similarity` | `0.6` | Abort below this unless `-y` or interactive confirm. |
| `-y`, `--yes` | off | Skip similarity guard. |
| `-i`, `--interactive` | off | Prompts for title, rank, low-similarity confirm. |
| `--api` | `arxiv` | `arxiv`, `crossref`, or `semantic_scholar`. |

```bash
python app.py match -t "Attention Is All You Need"
python app.py match -t "rough title guess" -y
python app.py match -t "BERT pretraining" --pick 2 -o bert_hit.bib
python app.py match -t "diffusion models" -n 200 --min-similarity 0.75 -y
python app.py match -i
python app.py -v match -t "graph neural network" -y -o gnn.bib

# Use different APIs
python app.py match -t "climate change" --api crossref
python app.py match -t "attention mechanism" --api semantic_scholar
```

---

## Command: `smart` (Markdown + inline citations)

```bash
python app.py smart --help
```

1. Reads **`input_md`** (tries **current working directory**, then **`refsproj1/`** if the path is relative and not found).
2. Strips optional **`---` … `---`** front matter from chunking; **re-emits it unchanged** at the top of the output.
3. Splits the **body** by **`--chunk-by`**: **`sentences`** (default) splits **per line** first, then sentences inside each line (handles `**Sentence.** **Next**`); **`paragraphs`** splits on blank lines. **`--chunk-n`** groups that many units into one search.
4. For each chunk: builds an `all:` keyword query (OR by default; see `src/filters.yaml`) from up to **`--query-words`** terms, searches arXiv with **`relevance`**, keeps **`--refs-per-chunk`** hits.
5. Assigns global **`[1]`, `[2]`, …**; same arXiv id → same number everywhere.
6. Appends citation markers **after** each chunk. **Paragraph** mode joins chunks with blank lines; **sentence** mode joins with spaces **within** each line so tables stay on one row.
7. Writes **`--output`** (default `refs/cited.md`).

| Flag | Default | Description |
|------|---------|-------------|
| `input_md` | *(required)* | Source Markdown path. |
| `-o`, `--output` | `cited.md` | Output `.md` (relative → `refs/`). |
| `--chunk-by` | `sentences` | `sentences` (default) or `paragraphs`. |
| `--chunk-n` | `1` | Group this many paragraphs or sentences per chunk. |
| `--refs-per-chunk` | `1` | Max references appended per chunk (`[1][2]…`). |
| `--query-words` | `8` | Max keywords per chunk for the search query. |
| `--ref-format` | `simple` | Reference block style (see below). |
| `--bibtex` | `none` | `none` \| `combined` \| `split`. |
| `--bibtex-output` | *(stem of `-o`)* | Path for **combined** `.bib` (relative → `refs/`). |
| `--api` | `arxiv` | `arxiv`, `crossref`, `semantic_scholar`, or `all` (merged). |

**`--ref-format`**

- **`simple`** — `[n] Title — URL`
- **`numbered`** — authors, year, source:id, URL (e.g., `arXiv:2401.12345`, `DOI:10.xxx`)
- **`links`** — Markdown link on title + id in backticks
- **`compact`** — `[n] title [id](url)`

**`--bibtex`**

- **`combined`** — one `.bib` (default: same stem as `-o`, e.g., `lit_review.md` → `lit_review.bib`).
- **`split`** — `refs/<output_stem>_bib/<id>.bib` per paper (id varies by source: arXiv ID, DOI, or S2 paper ID).
- **`none`** — no BibTeX files.

```bash
python app.py smart notes.md
python app.py smart draft.md -o lit_review.md --chunk-n 2 --refs-per-chunk 2
python app.py smart paper.md -o paper_cited.md --chunk-by sentences --chunk-n 3 --refs-per-chunk 2
python app.py smart chapter.md -o lit_review.md --ref-format numbered --bibtex combined
python app.py smart chapter.md -o lit_review.md --bibtex split
python app.py smart chapter.md -o out.md --bibtex combined --bibtex-output myrefs.bib
python app.py -v smart notes.md --query-words 5 -o cited.md

# Multi-API smart citations
python app.py smart notes.md --api crossref --refs-per-chunk 2
python app.py smart notes.md --api semantic_scholar --chunk-n 2
python app.py smart notes.md --api all --refs-per-chunk 3 --bibtex combined
```

**Limitations:** Search is **keyword-based**, not semantic; verify hits. Large files mean **many** HTTP calls (respect rate limits via `*_REQUEST_DELAY` env vars). Treat output as a **draft**.

---

## Windows: `app.bat`

```bat
cd /d D:\SAMs\refsproj1
app.bat bulk -q "cat:cs.CL" -n 5 -o out.bib
app.bat match -t "my paper title" -y
app.bat smart mynotes.md -o cited.md --refs-per-chunk 2
```

